3.3. Strain-displacement and stiï¬ness matrices The ï¬nal step in the element formulation is to construct the strain-displacement and stiï¬ness matrices. The covariant strain-displacement matrix corresponding to the 3D contravariant basis, deï¬ned in Eq. (16), is immediately obtained from Eq. (20) in terms of the nodal displacements and rotations. For the numerical implementation, it is somewhat involved to use the constitutive relationship in Eq. (22). A more eï¬ective way is to obtain the 3D strain components

in the global Cartesian coordinate system and employ the usual 3D constitutive relationship with the plane stress assumption imposed as shown, for example, in Ref. [1]. The stiï¬ness matrices of the shell ï¬nite elements based on the basic shell mathematical model are then calculated as the stiï¬ness matrices of the continuum mechanics based shell ï¬nite elements. These considerations and conclusions, as those in Section 3.2, are also applicable to the MITC shell elements because of the speciï¬c formulation of these elements, see Refs. [1,2,14]. The good convergence

