properties of these elements have been studied, for example, in Refs. [14,16,26]. 3.4. Numerical comparisons To this point, we reviewed the basic shell mathematical model and presented how to formulate a shell ï¬nite element discretization based on this model. As we pointed out, small diï¬erences must be expected in the solutions compared to those obtained with the continuum mechan-

ics based shell ï¬nite elements, because of the assumptions ~ used regarding V n and ~3 in each of the elements, see Fig. a 3. If, however, for the two formulations, the same element nodal points and the same interpolated element midsur~ faces are used, and ~3 is equal to V n , for every point in a the corresponding elements, then the same element stiï¬ness matrices are obtained. A trivial such case is the analysis of a plate. But also, we must expect that in the analysis of a smooth shell, this condition is always reached as the mesh is reï¬ned.

