In this section we demonstrate numerically by means of some examples that indeed even when using relatively coarse meshes, this diï¬erence is very small and that therefore the formulations are equivalent. Note that in these example solutions we do not measure the accuracy of the response predicted (compared to an exact or highly accurate solution) but only the diï¬erence in the response predicted using the two formulations. We also show in this section that it is important to interpolate the displacements as discussed in Section 3.2 (i.e. the rigid body mode criterion must be satisï¬ed). 3.4.1. Cylindrical shell problems We consider the well known cylindrical shell problems described in Fig. 4. The shell has uniform thickness t, length 2L and radius R and is subjected to the pressure distribution p(h) normal to the shell surface pÃ°hÃ Â¼ p0 cosÃ°2hÃ: Ã°53Ã

Depending on whether both ends are clamped or free, the asymptotic behavior of the structure is membrane dominated or bending dominated, respectively. By symmetry, the analyses are performed using one eighth of the structure, the shaded region ABCD in Fig. 4. The detailed description of the shell problems is presented in Refs. [12,14]. Using the continuum mechanics based shell ï¬nite element and the shell ï¬nite element based on the basic shell mathematical model, we compare the strain energy difference of the solutions obtained using the displacement based 6-node elements for both the membrane dominated and bending dominated shell problems as the element size h decreases. To investigate the dependence of the diï¬erence on the shell thickness, we consider the cases t/L = 1/100, t/L = 1/1000 and t/L = 1/10 000. The diï¬erence is calculated by jDEj jEC Ã EB j Â¼ ; EC EC Ã°54Ã

where EC and EB denote the strain energies of the solutions obtained with the continuum mechanics based shell ï¬nite element and the shell ï¬nite element based on the basic shell mathematical model, respectively. Fig. 5(a) and (b) report that for the clamped and free cases the strain energy diï¬erences between the solutions obtained using the two shell ï¬nite elements quickly vanish independent of the shell thickness as the element size decreases. Note that, when the element size is as large as L/2 (h = 0.5, that is, a 2 Â· 2 mesh is used.), the energy diï¬erence is already less than 0.1% and 0.3% for the clamped and free cases, respectively. We perform similar numerical tests for the shell ï¬nite element based on the basic shell mathematical model using the displacement interpolation in Eqs. (51) and (52). Fig. 6(a) and (b) shows that, when we use the displacement interpolation in Eqs. (51) and (52), as exempliï¬ed in the Appendix A, the results using the shell ï¬nite element based on the basic shell mathematical model are very diï¬erent to the results using the continuum mechanics based shell ï¬nite element for the free case and small shell thickness. Actually, the calculated strain energy is much too large. This is due to the fact that rigid body motions are not contained in the element formulation (see Appendix A). The need to be able to represent the rigid body modes is strikingly important in the case of the free cylinder and small shell thickness. 3.4.2. Partly clamped hyperbolic paraboloid shell problem The partly clamped hyperbolic paraboloid shell problem shown in Fig. 7 is a good bending dominated benchmark problem to test a formulation for locking, see Refs. [2,5,14]. The shell surface is deï¬ned by h 1 1 i2 z Â¼ x2 Ã y 2 ; Ã°x; yÃ 2 Ã ; Ã°55Ã 2 2 and clamped along the side x = Ã1/2. The structure is loaded by its self-weight (qgt = 80 per unit surface area). By symmetry, we can limit calculations to the shaded region ABCD in Fig. 7 with 