This solution is deemed accurate [26] and provides reference strain distributions. Figs. 10â13 and 14â17 show the reference strain distributions when t/L is 1/100 and 1/1000. These ï¬gures not only show the total strain components but also individual parts. It is important to see that, as the shell thickness decreases, there is an increasing diï¬erence in the orders of magnitudes between the membrane strain and its two parts, see Figs. 11 and 15. These ï¬gures show that both parts of the membrane strain are of opposite sign and in absolute values about three

and ï¬ve orders of magnitudes larger than the total membrane strain itself. A similar phenomenon is seen for the transverse shear strains and their individual parts, see Figs. 10(b), 13(b) and (c), 14(b) and 17(b) and (c). Table 1 summarizes the orders of the strain magnitudes in the reference solutions when the thickness ratios are 1/10, 1/100 and 1/1000. The order of the membrane strain is 10 times smaller than of its parts when t/ L = 1/10 but 105 times smaller when t/L = 1/1000. The same ratios also hold for the orders of the transverse shear strains.

Fig. 20. Distributions of the strain components of the free hyperboloid shell problem calculated using the MITC6 shell element with a 24 Â· 24 mesh, t/L = 1/1000: (a) the membrane strain; (b) the ï¬rst part of the membrane strain and (c) the second part of the membrane strain.

88

P.S. Lee, K.J. Bathe / Computers and Structures 83 (2005) 69â90

In a numerical solution, it is diï¬cult to calculate accurately a small value by summing two very large values and, as the two values grow, the diï¬culty increases. Clearly, this diï¬culty can be a major source of errors in the numerical solution of the shell problem. Indeed, as the shell thickness decreases, the increasing diï¬erence in the orders of the magnitudes between the membrane strain and its two parts can be a source of membrane locking and the increasing diï¬erence in the orders of the magnitudes between the transverse shear strain and its two parts can be a source of shear locking. 4.2. Detailed strain analysis using the MITC6 shell element In the previous section, we identiï¬ed why the free hyperboloid shell problem is diï¬cult to solve accurately. We next perform the same analysis as in the previous section using a uniform 24 Â· 24 mesh of the MITC6 [12] triangular shell ï¬nite elements based on the basic shell mathematical model. Ref. [12] reports that for the free hyperboloid shell problem the 6-node element shows some locking when the shell thickness is very small. As in Section 4.1, two cases of thickness, t/L = 1/100 and t/L = 1/1000, are considered. We show only the

membrane and transverse shear strains and their parts because these were recognized as diï¬cult to solve for. Indeed, the other strain components are accurately predicted in this solution. Figs. 18 and 19 display the distributions of the strain components of the free hyperboloid shell problem when t/L is 1/100. In this case, the solutions of the membrane and transverse shear strains are reasonably smooth but (except for the strain component â¬12) less smooth than their parts. The magnitudes of the solutions except for the transverse shear strain â¬13 (with predicted values however still reasonably small) are quite well predicted compared with the reference solutions. Figs. 20 and 21 show the solutions when t/L is 1/1000. It is interesting to note that the distributions of the membrane and transverse shear strains are not smooth and the magnitudes of the solutions are not accurate although their parts (except for the strain component â¬12) are quite well approximated. This numerical example using the MITC6 shell ï¬nite element demonstrates how the diï¬culty of calculating the strain components with large individual parts aï¬ects the ï¬nite element solution in the free hyperboloid shell problem. Clearly, the phenomenon we see is some membrane and shear locking.

Fig. 21. Distributions of the strain components of the free hyperboloid shell problem calculated using the MITC6 shell element; t/L = 1/1000: (a) the transverse shear strain; (b) the ï¬rst part of the transverse shear strain and (c) the second part of the transverse shear strain.

P.S. Lee, K.J. Bathe / Computers and Structures 83 (2005) 69â90

89

5. Conclusions The objective of this paper was to obtain new insight into the ï¬nite element discretization and solution of shell structures. For this purpose, we used the basic shell mathematical model to formulate shell ï¬nite elements that are equivalent to the widely-used continuum mechanics based shell ï¬nite elements, including the MITC elements. We showed that when ï¬nite elements are formulated based on a shell theory, it is important to ensure that the rigid body modes can be represented. If the interpolations used do not exactly admit rigid body modes, large errors can be present in the solution, in particular, if the shell is thin and a bending dominated condition is analyzed. Considering shell analysis, it is well known that large diï¬erences in magnitudes of the strain terms and their parts can arise. We highlighted this fact in this paper and presented the analysis of a shell structure for which the membrane and shear strain components contain parts of large magnitudes. These individual parts are orders of magnitudes larger than the actual strain components and these orders of magnitude diï¬erences quickly increase as a shell thickness decreases. Since each of the parts is calculated from diï¬erent displacement and rotation derivatives in the ï¬nite element solution, clearly difï¬culties in the development of eï¬ective shell elements must be anticipated and these relate to the well-known locking phenomena. While we concentrated here on the usually used ï¬ve degrees-of-freedom per node continuum mechanics based shell elements, these observations are, of course, also applicable when considering 3D shell elements and their underlying mathematical model [27]. The insight provided in this study should help to improve the mixed interpolation of strain components, or develop interpolations for their individual parts, in order to arrive at improved shell analysis capabilities.

